This was definitely a wonderful experience as this was my first time. The view is immaculate, especially since our reservation was booked for a time when the sun was just going down. Aviance along with the customer service was exquisite. Our server Anna was very attentive and she made knowledgeable recommendations while discussing the menu. The establishment was extremely clean and everyone certainly practiced social distancing. The gentleman downstairs when you first arrive was a little off-putting because we were not sure exactly what his purpose was while trying to check us in. Next, you have to get on the elevator to the top floor and go to another desk to confirm your reservation. We were seated promptly however I was a little disappointed because there was very very limited outside seating that really had an opportunity to take in the view so I will definitely try to get an outdoor table during my next visit. Also there is mention of a dress code on their website, however patrons arrived in ripped jeans, sneakers, etc and we're not dressed business casual . Had I known this would not have been strictly enforced I would have dressed down. Personally dressing nicely fits better considering the environment and the staff are dressed quite well. We were advised that their menu is seasonal, however the menu that was online did match what we were given so that was an added bonus. I will say that the portions are just enough so I certainly would not recommend coming here if you are over-the-top hungry. I did leave fulfilled not full but I had enough to eat. Everything that they had as a presentation regarding food and otherwise was amazing, however I was utterly disappointed that the Rockfish arrives in a bag as if it were a seafood boil that they cut open at the table before serving and placing on the table. It was almost as if I was eating out of a grocery bag. The macaroni and cheese had a much better presentation and it was in a small pan. The food tasted fresh and was definitely good but I would have rather them had different plating regarding the fish. The desserts are very small but tasty. The drinks are very nice. There was a drink that we tried and it was not to our liking and our server and was able to accommodate us by recommending something else which was an added bonus. The bottled water is $10 and it is a full bottle of Voss. Very attentive during the service and a busser will clear away any used and unneeded silverware and if there are any refills or anything that is needed someone is always there to assist. The service for this evening was flawless even down to the payment method. I would recommend this place for dining.

That's fine, and because of this he went across the street to J.Crew to buy attire and enter with the remainder of our group. On his way back in, another group was out of dress code and let in without the flinch of an eye. Once we all arrived upstairs, we were met by several guests in sweatshirts and sneakers. This made my group not only uncomfortable, but feel highly discriminated against. We approached the manager Julian with our discomfort, and he sent their doorman to sit at our table and argue with us about his reasoning for letting the others out of dress code in and not my group. Throughout our experience at The Bygone, our cocktail waitress gave us attitude and rolled her eyes the entire time. We overheard her speaking with a bartender about our group and belittling us. Discrimination and racism aside, this venue served subpar cocktails and needs to reevaluate their interpretation of the word hospitality. We were not after a free drink, we are accustomed to several rounds of $25 cocktails in NYC coupled with unparalleled service. I don't recommend this establishment unless you are after an amateur waitstaff. Save your money unless you enjoy lack of professionalism, cheaply made drinks and a horrific experience. Shame on you Four Seasons.

A major part of the experience here was the view, so being sat in a corner with bright orange tape took away from the 1920s experience. The hostess took 45 minutes to seat us after we had arrived for our reservation. We initially waited 20 minutes and then asked if we could sit at the bar until our table was ready. We received a text notification right before we ordered our drinks (about 10 minutes later) so we left the bar empty handed. At that point the hostess told us we actually had to wait about another 15 minutes before we could actually be seated - so we could have stayed at the bar until receiving a second text confirmation about our table. The highlights of this experience were the entertaining elevator host, the views of the city, the decor, the food, and the knowledgable waiter. I've been putting off writing this because I only want to say nice things. And now 2 months have gone by with no response from the restaurant after I sent them the following letter. So now this goes public: Bygone is the place that Baltimore sorely needs. We've been to Michelin starred restaurants all over Europe and Asia and we consider ourselves foodies and appreciate truly wonderful service. We don't mind paying for it either. However, on our recent visit for my husband's birthday, I made a reservation and brought my parents, whom we aren't able to see very often due to scheduling difficulties and distance. My mother was very much looking forward to trying the Dover sole and my husband the Amish chicken. Neither was available. My mother's second choice was likewise not available. How disappointing! Our waiter kept joking that we'd have to come back to try them. We already see my parents only once or twice a year. I hardly think I'll open them up to this disappointment again! I'm sure my husband and I will make an attempt, but of course, not with them. I feel that when you offer a $95 entree and people come in excited to try it, and that's the first thing they say when they sit down, you should maybe mention that you're out of it. Oh, and don't EVER be out of it. My parents just returned from a trip to Russia, and so were excited to order caviar, but we joked that it probably wasn't available, and so did not order it. We were tired of being told no. Otherwise, the service was excellent, the drinks were spot-on. We have no complaints about our second and third choices, but that's what they were--not what we came for. At least we got our views of the city. I just wanted to explain that people do come for the food experience as well. Also, my husband's birthday was never acknowledged. Perhaps that sort of thing is not done at such an upscale place, but I will say that the Ritz in Hong Kong made quite an unexpected spectacle of our anniversary, so that can't be it. Maybe it was forgotten. Surprising for so grand a place. It's so difficult to get a reservation at your restaurant, and equally difficult to get your choice of entree! It's unfortunate, because I really would have loved to. What a shame.
